n how squares, triangles, and circles take shape in the cubic, triangular, and cylindrical forms that comprise houses and other buildings. Then black-and-white photographs, the heart of the book, illustrate these geometric forms in historic and modern buildings. The book also includes two essays in which Heimsath discusses the factors that led him and his wife Maryann to document early Texas buildings and the results in historic preservation and timeless architectural designs that have followed from their efforts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aGeometry in architecturezTexasvPictorial works. 0aVernacular architecturezTexasvPictorial works. 7aARCHITECTURE / General.2bisacsh1 aHardaway, Lisa.1 aHeimsath, Maryann.1 aKahn, Louis I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahn, Louis.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/73145540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292759770423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292759770/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK